{{Malay name|Azim Izamuddin|Suhaimi}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Azim Izamuddin | fullname = Muhammad Azim Izamuddin bin Haji Suhaimi | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|05|20|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Brunei]] | height = | position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]] | currentclub = [[DPMM FC]] | clubnumber = 16 | youthyears1 =2013–2014 | youthclubs1 = [[Majlis Sukan Sekolah-Sekolah Brunei Darussalam|MSSSBD]] | youthyears2 =2015 | youthclubs2 = [[Tabuan Muda]] | youthyears3 =2015–2016 | youthclubs3 = [[DPMM FC]] | years1 = 2015 | caps1 = | goals1 = | clubs1 = [[Tabuan U18]] | years2 = 2016– | caps2 = 5 | goals2 = 0| clubs2 = [[DPMM FC]] | nationalyears1= 2017– | nationalcaps1= 3 | nationalgoals1= 1 | nationalteam1= [[Brunei national under-23 football team|Brunei U23]] | nationalyears2= 2018 | nationalcaps2= 3 | nationalgoals2= 0 | nationalteam2= [[Brunei national under-21 football team|Brunei U21]] | club-update = 12 March 2018 | ntupdate = 1 May 2018 }}
'''Muhammad Azim Izamuddin bin Haji Suhaimi''' (born 20 May 1997) is a [[Brunei]]an [[Association football|footballer]] who plays professionally for [[DPMM FC]] of the [[Singapore]]an [[S.League]] as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kean on most potent attacking force|url=http://borneobulletin.com.bn/kean-on-most-potent-attacking-force/|date=16 March 2016|publisher=[[Borneo Bulletin]]|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
Azim was a participant of the footballing scheme run by Brunei Darussalam Schools' Sports Council (MSSSBD) under the Ministry of Education, whilst attending [[Sayyidina Hasan Secondary School]].<ref>{{cite web |title=NFABD-TELBRU Under 16 Football League |url=http://www.rtbnews.rtb.gov.bn/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10760%3Anfabd-telbru-under-16-football-league&Itemid=80|date=19 May 2013|publisher=[[Radio Television Brunei]]|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> He was soon scouted by Brunei's football association [[National Football Association of Brunei Darussalam|NFABD]] and placed him in the [[Tabuan Muda|Tabuan Under-18 team]] in the 2015 [[Brunei Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Maten powers Tabuan U-18|url=http://www.nfabd.org/news/2015041201.htm|date=12 April 2015|publisher=[[The Brunei Times]]|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
Azim attended a tryout for DPMM FC's Under-19 team in early 2015 and was selected by [[Steve Kean]] as the team's captain.<ref>{{cite web |title=DPMM FC youth trial Sunday|url=http://borneobulletin.com.bn/dpmm-fc-youth-trial-sunday/|date=7 January 2015|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=DPMM FC set qualifying time in 2.4km test|url=http://borneobulletin.com.bn/dpmm-fc-set-qualifying-time-in-2-4km-test/|date=11 February 2016|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> He progressed well through the ranks and was awarded with a promotion to the first team at the start of the [[2016 S.League]] season, alongside [[Abdul Hafiz Abdul Rahim]] and [[Na'im Tarif]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/sg/features/kean-setting-bar-high-defending-champions-dpmm|title=Kean setting the bar high for defending champions DPMM|publisher=[[FourFourTwo]] Singapore|date=12 February 2016|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> He made his competitive debut in a 3–0 loss to [[Ceres F.C.|Ceres-La Salle]] in the quarterfinals of the [[2016 Singapore Cup]] on 30 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=DPMM FC Lost to Ceres La Salle 3-0|url=https://www.brudirect.com/news.php?id=8150|date=1 July 2016|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
On 21 July, Azim came on as a second-half substitute against [[Tampines Rovers]] and later capitalized on a mistake from [[Joey Sim]] to score the winner of the match, enabling DPMM to qualify as group winners in the [[2016 Singapore League Cup]] group stage.<ref>{{cite web |title=The New Paper League Cup 2016: Akbar’s 100 Percent Stags Record Ended By Resurgent Wasps|url=http://sleague.com/news-features/news/2016/january/amri-takes-on-big-brother-role-at-young-lions/the-new-paper-league-cup-2016-akbar-s-100-percent-stags-record-ended-by-resurgent-wasps|date=22 July 2016|publisher=[[S.League]]|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> His team went all the way to the final later that month, but Azim could only watch from the bench as DPMM lose to [[Albirex Niigata Singapore FC|Albirex Niigata (S)]] in a 0–2 scoreline.<ref>{{cite web |title=DPMM vs. Albirex Niigata S 0 - 2|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/07/30/singapore/league-cup/brunei-dpmm/albirex-niigate-fc/2318161/|date=|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> Azim finally made his [[S.League]] debut on 11 August in a 1–1 stalemate against [[Geylang International FC|Geylang International]], coming on as an 82nd-minute substitute.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geylang International vs. DPMM 1 - 1|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/08/11/singapore/sleague/geylang-united-fc/brunei-dpmm/2186856/|date=|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
==International career==
Azim was selected for the [[2018 AFC U-23 Championship qualification]] matches held in [[Myanmar]] in July 2017, his first involvement with the national team at any level.<ref>{{cite web |title=AFC U-23 CHAMPIONSHIP 2018 QUALIFIERS SQUAD LIST: Brunei Darussalam|url=http://www.the-afc.com/afcasfeeds?stageid=436&tMode=C&fixtureid=11375&teamid=1032&view=ajax&show=finalregistration|date=|publisher=Asian Football Confederation|accessdate=20 July 2017}}</ref> He made his debut in the first group game against [[Australia national under-23 soccer team|Australia]] as a second-half substitute in a 2-0 loss. He started the third and final game against [[Singapore national under-23 football team|Singapore]] and scored a consolation for the Young Wasps in the 1–4 defeat.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brunei end AFC U-23 C’Ship qualifiers with loss to Singapore|url=https://www.brusports.com/2017/07/24/brunei-end-afc-u-23-cship-qualifiers-with-loss-to-singapore/|date=24 July 2017|publisher=BruSports News|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>
One year later, he was selected for the [[2018 Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy]] with the [[Brunei national under-21 football team|under-21s]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Faiq Jefri Bolkiah to lead national team|url=https://borneobulletin.com.bn/faiq-jefri-bolkiah-to-lead-national-team/|date=22 April 2018|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> He started the opening match on 23 April, which was a 0-1 loss against [[Timor-Leste national under-21 football team|Timor-Leste]]. He was relegated to the substitutes' bench in their second game against [[Thailand national under-19 football team|Thailand]], but came on later in the match and took the corner that club teammate [[Yura Indera Putera Yunos|Yura Yunos]] scored the winner from.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brunei edge Thailand in last-gasp win|url=https://borneobulletin.com.bn/brunei-edge-thailand-in-last-gasp-win/|date=28 April 2018|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>
