{{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Bainton Field | nickname = | image = | fullname = | location = [[Piscataway, New Jersey]] | coordinates = {{coord|40.527232|-74.443295|type:landmark}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = | renovated = 2007 | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Rutgers University]] | operator = [[Rutgers University]] | surface = Field Turf | construction_cost = | architect = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor= | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = Class of 1953 Complex - Gruninger Baseball Complex | tenants = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights]] baseball (1953-Present) | seating_capacity = 1,500 | dimensions = LL - 330 LC - 385 CF - 410 RC - 370 RL - 320 }}
'''Bainton Field''' is a [[baseball]] [[stadium]] in [[Piscataway, New Jersey]]. It is the home field of the [[Rutgers-New Brunswick|Rutgers University]] Scarlet Knights [[college baseball]] team. The stadium holds 1,500 spectators.
==History== Baseball at Rutgers has the distinction of being the first intercollegiate athletic event to be held at the university. The game was played on May 2, 1866 against [[Princeton University|Princeton]] in which Rutgers lost 40-2.<ref name="years">{{cite web|title=The First Game: Nov. 6, 1869|url=http://www.scarletknights.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/first-game.html|publisher=Rutgers, The State University of New Jersey|accessdate=August 2, 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006153050/http://www.scarletknights.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/first-game.html|archivedate=October 6, 2014|df=}}</ref>
The original name of the facility was the "Class of 1953 Complex - Gruninger Baseball Complex"; however, in 2007, the stadium was renamed in honor of Ron Bainton, an alumnus who graduated from Rutgers in 1962. Bainton donated $1.25 million to renovate the stadium and for ongoing enhancements in the future. Renovations to the stadium included: a new [[FieldTurf]] playing surface, the construction of a new [[outfield]] wall, as well as on-field facilities to include a practice diamond and three full length batting cages and five practice pitching mounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bainton Field|url=http://www.scarletknights.com/facilities/?id=7|publisher=Rutgers University Athletics|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>
On August 21, 2015, the Rutgers Athletics department announced a $3.3 million dollar project to construct an indoor training facility for the baseball and softball teams. The Fred Hill Training Complex, named after long-time Rutgers head baseball coach [[Fred Hill (coach)|Fred Hill]], will be located between Bainton Field and the Rutgers softball complex. The facility is estimated to be approximately 22,500 sq. feet and utilize state-of-the-art pitching machines, batting cages, bullpen mounds and a full turf infield.
On October 24, 2015, construction began on the Fred Hill Training Complex with a groundbreaking ceremony held prior to the football game between [[2015 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]] and [[2015 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rutgers Athletics Announces Construction of Fred Hill Training Complex|url=http://www.scarletknights.com/news/2015/8/21/Rutgers_Athletics_Announces_Construction_of_Fred_Hill_Training_Complex.aspx|publisher=Rutgers University Athletics|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> The new indoor practice complex is part of a larger athletic facilities upgrade sponsored by the university, which will also include, but is not limited to, expansion of Bainton Field capacity to approximately 2,000-3,000 seats and a new softball facility.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rutgers unveils plan for new and updated athletics facilities|url=http://www.app.com/story/sports/college/rutgers/2015/06/18/rutgers-unveils-athletic-facilities-plan-bog/28937999/|publisher=App.com|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>
